('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 1, 'multiple_choice', 'Ethics', 'What creates conflicts of interest when Elon Musk serves as both presidential advisor and government contractor?', 'No conflicts exist', 'Personal financial interests in government decisions affecting his companies', 'Enhanced government efficiency', 'Improved business practices', 'Personal financial interests in government decisions affecting his companies', 'Advisors shouldn\'t have financial stakes in policies they influence.', 'Conflicts of interest arise when Elon Musk serves as both presidential advisor and government contractor because he has personal financial interests in government decisions that affect his companies like SpaceX, Tesla, and Starlink, creating competing loyalties between public service and private profit.', '["conflicts of interest", "dual roles", "financial interests"]', '[{"name": "Office of Government Ethics - Conflict Laws", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/Web/oge.nsf/Resources/Conflicts+of+Interest"}, {"name": "Government Accountability Office - Ethics Analysis", "url": "https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-18-253"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Executive Branch Ethics", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 2, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What federal law prohibits officials from participating in matters affecting their financial interests?', 'Federal Election Campaign Act', '18 USC 208', 'Administrative Procedure Act', 'Government in the Sunshine Act', '18 USC 208', 'This criminal statute specifically addresses financial conflicts of interest.', '18 USC 208 prohibits federal officials from participating in any matter in which they have a financial interest. This criminal statute would apply to situations where Musk\'s advisory role could influence government decisions affecting his business interests.', '["18 USC 208", "criminal conflict law", "financial participation"]', '[{"name": "18 USC 208 - Criminal Conflict of Interest Statute", "url": "https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2011-title18/pdf/USCODE-2011-title18-partI-chap11-sec208.pdf"}, {"name": "Office of Government Ethics - Criminal Statutes", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/Web/oge.nsf/Resources/Criminal+Conflict+of+Interest+Statutes"}, {"name": "Department of Justice - Public Integrity", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/criminal/pin"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 3, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'Which of Musk\'s companies have significant government contracts?', 'Only Tesla', 'SpaceX and Starlink', 'None of his companies', 'Only social media companies', 'SpaceX and Starlink', 'These companies provide space launch and satellite internet services to government.', 'SpaceX and Starlink have significant government contracts providing space launch services to NASA and the Department of Defense, and satellite internet services to various government agencies. These contracts create financial interests that could conflict with Musk\'s advisory role.', '["SpaceX contracts", "Starlink services", "government business"]', '[{"name": "NASA - SpaceX Contracts", "url": "https://www.nasa.gov/news/releases/nasa-spacex-contracts/"}, {"name": "Department of Defense - Space Contracts", "url": "https://www.defense.gov/News/Contracts/"}, {"name": "Federal Procurement Data System", "url": "https://www.fpds.gov/"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 4, 'multiple_choice', 'Ethics', 'What is the "appearance of impropriety" standard in government ethics?', 'Only actual corruption matters', 'Officials should avoid actions that appear conflicted to reasonable observers', 'Appearance standards don\'t apply to advisors', 'No such standard exists', 'Officials should avoid actions that appear conflicted to reasonable observers', 'Ethics requires avoiding both actual and apparent conflicts.', 'The "appearance of impropriety" standard requires government officials to avoid actions that could appear corrupt or conflicted to reasonable observers, even without actual wrongdoing. This maintains public trust by ensuring government actions appear legitimate and ethical.', '["appearance of impropriety", "ethical standards", "public trust"]', '[{"name": "Office of Government Ethics - Appearance Standards", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/Web/oge.nsf/Resources/Standards+of+Ethical+Conduct"}, {"name": "American Bar Association - Ethics Rules", "url": "https://www.americanbar.org/groups/professional_responsibility/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Ethics Standards", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 5, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'How do conflicts of interest affect separation of powers?', 'They strengthen separation of powers', 'They can undermine checks and balances by creating competing loyalties', 'They have no effect on separation of powers', 'They only affect the judicial branch', 'They can undermine checks and balances by creating competing loyalties', 'Officials must serve the public interest rather than private gain.', 'Conflicts of interest can undermine separation of powers by creating competing loyalties between public duties and private financial interests, potentially compromising the independence and integrity needed for effective checks and balances between government branches.', '["separation of powers", "competing loyalties", "institutional integrity"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Separation of Powers Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/separation-of-powers/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Separation of Powers", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R42733"}, {"name": "Federalist Papers - Separation of Powers", "url": "https://guides.loc.gov/federalist-papers/separation-of-powers"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 6, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'What oversight mechanisms exist for monitoring conflicts of interest?', 'No oversight mechanisms exist', 'Office of Government Ethics, congressional oversight, and inspector generals', 'Only media oversight', 'Self-regulation exclusively', 'Office of Government Ethics, congressional oversight, and inspector generals', 'Multiple institutions monitor compliance with ethics laws.', 'Oversight of conflicts of interest involves the Office of Government Ethics providing guidance and monitoring, congressional oversight through hearings and investigations, and inspector generals reviewing compliance with ethics laws and regulations.', '["ethics oversight", "OGE", "congressional monitoring"]', '[{"name": "Office of Government Ethics", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/"}, {"name": "House Oversight Committee", "url": "https://oversight.house.gov/"}, {"name": "Council of Inspectors General", "url": "https://www.ignet.gov/"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 7, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What constitutional principle requires faithful execution of laws without personal bias?', 'Due Process Clause', 'Take Care Clause', 'Equal Protection Clause', 'Commerce Clause', 'Take Care Clause', 'This constitutional provision requires presidents to ensure laws are faithfully executed.', 'The Take Care Clause in Article II, Section 3 requires the President to "take care that the laws be faithfully executed," creating a constitutional duty to ensure impartial enforcement without personal financial bias or conflicts of interest.', '["Take Care Clause", "faithful execution", "constitutional duty"]', '[{"name": "Constitution - Take Care Clause", "url": "https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/essay/artII-S3-1/"}, {"name": "Supreme Court - Take Care Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/executive-power/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Presidential Duties", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R42733"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 8, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'How do business relationships with advisors affect government procurement decisions?', 'They improve procurement efficiency', 'They can create unfair advantages and undermine competitive bidding', 'They have no effect on procurement', 'They always reduce costs', 'They can create unfair advantages and undermine competitive bidding', 'Fair competition requires officials to avoid conflicts of interest.', 'Business relationships with advisors can create unfair advantages in government procurement by potentially influencing contract decisions, undermining competitive bidding processes, and raising questions about whether awards are based on merit rather than personal relationships.', '["government procurement", "unfair advantages", "competitive bidding"]', '[{"name": "Federal Acquisition Regulation", "url": "https://www.acquisition.gov/far/"}, {"name": "Government Accountability Office - Procurement", "url": "https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-19-196"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Federal Contracting", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R40516"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 9, 'multiple_choice', 'Ethics', 'What remedies exist when conflicts of interest violations occur?', 'No remedies are available', 'Divestiture, recusal, termination, and criminal prosecution', 'Only resignation', 'Warning letters exclusively', 'Divestiture, recusal, termination, and criminal prosecution', 'Multiple enforcement mechanisms exist for ethics violations.', 'Remedies for conflicts of interest violations include requiring divestiture of conflicting financial interests, recusal from relevant decisions, termination from government position, and potential criminal prosecution under conflict of interest statutes.', '["ethics remedies", "divestiture", "criminal prosecution"]', '[{"name": "Office of Government Ethics - Remedies", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/Web/oge.nsf/Resources/Ethics+Enforcement"}, {"name": "Department of Justice - Ethics Prosecution", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/criminal/pin"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Ethics Enforcement", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 10, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'How do technology industry conflicts affect national security policy?', 'They improve national security', 'They can compromise objective policy-making on critical technologies', 'They have no security implications', 'They only affect commercial interests', 'They can compromise objective policy-making on critical technologies', 'National security requires objective analysis free from personal interests.', 'Technology industry conflicts can compromise national security policy by potentially biasing decisions about critical technologies, space policy, artificial intelligence regulation, and other strategic areas where personal business interests might conflict with national security objectives.', '["national security", "technology policy", "objective decision-making"]', '[{"name": "National Security Council", "url": "https://www.whitehouse.gov/nsc/"}, {"name": "Department of Defense - Technology Strategy", "url": "https://www.defense.gov/News/technology/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - National Security Technology", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R46795"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 11, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What due process concerns arise from conflicts of interest in government decisions?', 'No due process concerns exist', 'Unfair treatment when personal interests influence official decisions', 'Enhanced due process protections', 'Only procedural issues', 'Unfair treatment when personal interests influence official decisions', 'Due process requires fair and impartial treatment by government.', 'Due process concerns arise when conflicts of interest may lead to unfair treatment because personal financial interests could influence official decisions, potentially denying equal treatment under law and fair consideration based on legal merit rather than personal relationships.', '["due process", "fair treatment", "equal consideration"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Due Process Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/due-process/"}, {"name": "Constitutional Law - Due Process Analysis", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/due_process"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Due Process Rights", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45031"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 12, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'What transparency requirements apply to government advisor financial interests?', 'No transparency requirements', 'Financial disclosure forms and conflict identification', 'Complete secrecy required', 'Only voluntary disclosure', 'Financial disclosure forms and conflict identification', 'Ethics laws require disclosure of potential conflicts.', 'Government advisors are subject to transparency requirements including financial disclosure forms that identify potential conflicts of interest, allowing oversight bodies and the public to monitor compliance with ethics laws and identify potential problems.', '["financial disclosure", "transparency requirements", "conflict identification"]', '[{"name": "Office of Government Ethics - Financial Disclosure", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/Web/oge.nsf/Resources/Financial+Disclosure"}, {"name": "Ethics in Government Act", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/5a/appendix-4"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Ethics Disclosure", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 13, 'multiple_choice', 'Ethics', 'How do conflicts of interest affect public trust in government?', 'They improve public trust', 'They undermine confidence in fair and impartial governance', 'They have no effect on public opinion', 'They only affect business confidence', 'They undermine confidence in fair and impartial governance', 'Citizens must believe government serves the public interest.', 'Conflicts of interest undermine public trust by creating doubt about whether government decisions serve the public interest or private financial gain, potentially damaging confidence in democratic institutions and fair governance.', '["public trust", "democratic legitimacy", "institutional confidence"]', '[{"name": "Pew Research - Trust in Government", "url": "https://www.pewresearch.org/politics/2019/09/19/public-trust-in-government-1958-2019/"}, {"name": "American Bar Association - Public Trust Survey", "url": "https://www.americanbar.org/advocacy/rule_of_law/public-trust-survey/"}, {"name": "Brookings Institution - Government Trust", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/research/public-trust-government/"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 14, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'What role does congressional oversight play in monitoring conflicts of interest?', 'No congressional role exists', 'Investigations, hearings, and subpoena power to examine violations', 'Only advisory opinions', 'Passive monitoring exclusively', 'Investigations, hearings, and subpoena power to examine violations', 'Congress has constitutional oversight responsibilities.', 'Congressional oversight of conflicts of interest includes conducting investigations, holding hearings, using subpoena power to obtain documents and testimony, and ensuring compliance with ethics laws through active monitoring and enforcement.', '["congressional oversight", "investigations", "subpoena power"]', '[{"name": "House Oversight Committee", "url": "https://oversight.house.gov/"}, {"name": "Senate Ethics Committee", "url": "https://www.ethics.senate.gov/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Congressional Oversight", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45442"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 15, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'How do international business interests create additional conflict concerns?', 'They reduce conflict concerns', 'They can compromise national security and foreign policy decisions', 'They have no additional implications', 'They only affect trade policy', 'They can compromise national security and foreign policy decisions', 'Foreign business interests can influence U.S. policy decisions.', 'International business interests create additional conflict concerns because they can potentially compromise national security assessments, foreign policy decisions, and diplomatic relationships when personal financial interests in foreign markets might influence official U.S. government positions.', '["international conflicts", "national security", "foreign policy"]', '[{"name": "National Security Council - Conflict Guidelines", "url": "https://www.whitehouse.gov/nsc/"}, {"name": "Department of State - Ethics Requirements", "url": "https://www.state.gov/ethics/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Foreign Conflicts", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 16, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'What enforcement mechanisms exist for criminal conflict of interest violations?', 'No enforcement mechanisms', 'Federal prosecution by Department of Justice', 'Only civil penalties', 'State court jurisdiction exclusively', 'Federal prosecution by Department of Justice', 'Criminal violations are prosecuted by federal authorities.', 'Criminal conflict of interest violations under 18 USC 208 are enforced through federal prosecution by the Department of Justice, which can result in fines, imprisonment, and removal from government position for officials who violate conflict laws.', '["criminal enforcement", "DOJ prosecution", "federal penalties"]', '[{"name": "Department of Justice - Public Integrity Section", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/criminal/pin"}, {"name": "18 USC 208 - Criminal Penalties", "url": "https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2011-title18/pdf/USCODE-2011-title18-partI-chap11-sec208.pdf"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Ethics Enforcement", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

('2025-04-02-musk-trump-conflicts', 17, 'multiple_choice', 'Ethics', 'What principles should guide resolution of conflicts between advisory roles and business interests?', 'Business interests should always take priority', 'Public service obligations should take precedence over private gain', 'No principles are needed', 'Equal weight to both interests', 'Public service obligations should take precedence over private gain', 'Government service requires prioritizing public interest over personal benefit.', 'Resolution of conflicts between advisory roles and business interests should be guided by the principle that public service obligations take precedence over private gain, ensuring that government decisions serve the public interest rather than personal financial benefit.', '["public service ethics", "public interest", "conflict resolution"]', '[{"name": "Office of Government Ethics - Ethical Principles", "url": "https://www.oge.gov/Web/oge.nsf/Resources/Standards+of+Ethical+Conduct"}, {"name": "American Bar Association - Public Service Ethics", "url": "https://www.americanbar.org/groups/professional_responsibility/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Ethics Principles", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R43186"}]'),

